amen_secundum)\n-   [Edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit \"Edit this page [e]\")\n-   [View history](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=history \"Past revisions of this page [h]\")\n\n Tools\n\nTools\n\nmove to sidebar hide\n\nActions\n\n-   [Read](/wiki/Foramen_secundum)\n-   [Edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit \"Edit this page [e]\")\n-   [View history](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=history)\n\nGeneral\n\n-   [What links here](/wiki/Special:WhatLinksHere/Foramen_secundum \"List of all English Wikipedia pages containing links to this page [j]\")\n-   [Related changes](/wiki/Special:RecentChangesLinked/Foramen_secundum \"Recent changes in pages linked from this page [k]\")\n-   [Upload file](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:File_Upload_Wizard \"Upload files [u]\")\n-   [Permanent link](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&oldid=1300057166 \"Permanent link to this revision of this page\")\n-   [Page information](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=info \"More information about this page\")\n-   [Cite this page](/w/index.php?title=Special:CiteThisPage&page=Foramen_secundum&id=1300057166&wpFormIdentifier=titleform \"Information on how to cite this page\")\n-   [Get shortened URL](/w/index.php?title=Special:UrlShortener&url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FForamen_secundum)\n\nPrint/export\n\n-   [Download as PDF](/w/index.php?title=Special:DownloadAsPdf&page=Foramen_secundum&action=show-download-screen \"Download this page as a PDF file\")\n-   [Printable version](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&printable=yes \"Printable version of this page [p]\")\n\nIn other projects\n\n-   [Wikidata item](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Special:EntityPage/Q5467185 \"Structured data on this page hosted by Wikidata [g]\")\n\nAppearance\n\nmove to sidebar hide\n\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\n\nForamen secundum\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bf/Foramen_ovale.png)](/wiki/File:Foramen_ovale.png)\n\nBlood, shown in the red arrow, travels through the foramen ovale and the foramen secundum. HH: [right ventricle](/wiki/Right_ventricle \"Right ventricle\"), VH: left ventricle, HF: right atrium, VF: left atrium, LV: pulmonary vein\n\nDetails\n\nDays\n\n33\n\nIdentifiers\n\n[Latin](/wiki/Latin \"Latin\")\n\n*foramen secundum*\n\n[TE](/wiki/Terminologia_Embryologica \"Terminologia Embryologica\")\n\n[secundum\\_by\\_E5.11.1.5.2.1.2 E5.11.1.5.2.1.2](https://ifaa.unifr.ch/Public/EntryPage/THE/TE2010V1.pdf#page=85?note=Linked_from_Foramen)\n\n[Anatomical terminology](/wiki/Anatomical_terminology \"Anatomical terminology\")\n\n\\[[edit on Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q5467185 \"d:Q5467185\")\\]\n\nThe **foramen secundum** or **ostium secundum** is a *[foramen](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/foramen#English \"wikt:foramen\")* in the [septum primum](/wiki/Septum_primum \"Septum primum\"), a precursor to the [interatrial septum](/wiki/Interatrial_septum \"Interatrial septum\") of the [human heart](/wiki/Human_heart \"Human heart\").\n\nIt is not the same as the [foramen ovale](/wiki/Foramen_ovale_\\(heart\\) \"Foramen ovale (heart)\"), which is an opening in the [septum secundum](/wiki/Septum_secundum \"Septum secundum\").\n\n## Development\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=1 \"Edit section: Development\")\\]\n\nMain article: [Interatrial septum § Development](/wiki/Interatrial_septum#Development \"Interatrial septum\")\n\nThe foramen secundum (from [Latin](/wiki/Latin_language \"Latin language\") 'second opening') is formed from small perforations that develop in the [septum primum](/wiki/Septum_primum \"Septum primum\"). The septum primum is a *[septum](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/septum#English \"wikt:septum\")* that grows down between the single [primitive atrium](/wiki/Primitive_atrium \"Primitive atrium\") of the [developing heart](/wiki/Heart_development \"Heart development\") to separate it into [left](/wiki/Left_atrium \"Left atrium\") and [right atria](/wiki/Right_atrium \"Right atrium\").[\\[1\\]](#cite_note-gary-1)\n\n### Closure\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=2 \"Edit section: Closure\")\\]\n\nOnce a baby is born, blood should flow through the lungs, which now function to provide oxygen to the blood. The foramen secundum and [foramen ovale](/wiki/Foramen_ovale_\\(heart\\) \"Foramen ovale (heart)\") act as a [shunt](/wiki/Shunt_\\(medical\\) \"Shunt (medical)\") where blood bypasses the lungs and does not become oxygenated. To provide proper blood flow as a newborn, the foramen secundum and foramen ovale must close at birth. Since the lungs now require a significant amount of blood flow, the vessels going to and from the lungs undergo dilation. While the [pulmonary artery](/wiki/Pulmonary_artery \"Pulmonary artery\") and [pulmonary veins](/wiki/Pulmonary_veins \"Pulmonary veins\") are dilating, the [umbilical artery](/wiki/Umbilical_artery \"Umbilical artery\") and [umbilical vein](/wiki/Umbilical_vein \"Umbilical vein\") are severed at the cutting of the [umbilical cord](/wiki/Umbilical_cord \"Umbilical cord\"), or the funiculus umbilicalis. This combination results in a reversal of pressure differences between the atria, and the septum primum is permanently forced against the septum secundum. This holds true even during atrial [diastole](/wiki/Diastole \"Diastole\"), when the pressure is significantly less than atrial [systole](/wiki/Systole_\\(medicine\\) \"Systole (medicine)\").[\\[1\\]](#cite_note-gary-1)\n\n## Function\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=3 \"Edit section: Function\")\\]\n\nThe septum primum is on the left side of the heart in the [left atrium](/wiki/Left_atrium \"Left atrium\") while the septum secundum is much thicker and is located on the right side, in the [right atrium](/wiki/Right_atrium \"Right atrium\"). During development, blood shunts from the floor of the right atrium through the foramen ovale in the septum secundum then up through the foramen secundum in the septum primum.[\\[2\\]](#cite_note-2) The foramen secundum is positioned so that blood exits in the ceiling of the left atrium and then out through the [left ventricle](/wiki/Left_ventricle \"Left ventricle\") and the [aorta](/wiki/Aorta \"Aorta\"). The position of the foramen secundum and the size of the septum primum are crucial to ensuring that blood not flow backwards from the left atrium to the right atrium. The septum primum, being much thinner, is easily pressed against the septum secundum if blood attempts to flow in the reverse direction, effectively sealing off both the foramen secundum and the foramen ovale.[\\[1\\]](#cite_note-gary-1)\n\n## Clinical significance\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=4 \"Edit section: Clinical significance\")\\]\n\nAn ostium secundum that persists at large size can be a source of [atrial septal defects](/wiki/Atrial_septal_defect \"Atrial septal defect\").[\\[3\\]](#cite_note-3) Foramen secundum atrial septal defects are the most common atrial septal defects. This defect can arise as a result of defects of the septum primum and the septum secundum. For the septum primum, the problem can arise as a result of excess resorption of the septum during the process of apoptosis in order to form the foramen secundum. For the septum secundum, its inadequate growth can cause atrial septal defect since it is supposed to grow and eventually overlap the foramen secundum so as to form the oval foramen. As the right atrial pressure is normally lower than the mean left atrial pressure, a persisting ostium secundum causes usually a left-to-right shunt (meaning that blood flows from the left to the right atrium, wherefore it is an [azyanotic heart defect](/wiki/Acyanotic_heart_defect \"Acyanotic heart defect\")).[\\[4\\]](#cite_note-4)\n\n### Treatment\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=5 \"Edit section: Treatment\")\\]\n\nNewborns with small foramen secundum atrial septal defects have been shown to spontaneously correct by the third or fourth year of life.[\\[5\\]](#cite_note-5) Therefore, medical supervision is generally accepted as a preventive measure for those diagnosed in infancy, rather than surgical intervention or use of other medical devices.[\\[6\\]](#cite_note-6)\n\nIf surgery is required, it is performed using minimally invasive techniques via robotic surgery that often requires only a few days of hospital stay.[\\[7\\]](#cite_note-7) Surgical intervention should result in full closure of the foramen secundum, and mortality rates are similar to those for [general anesthesia](/wiki/General_anesthesia \"General anesthesia\").[\\[8\\]](#cite_note-8) The repair can be made by suturing the atrial septum or, if the foramen secundum is large in size, a patch can be made from the patient's [pericardium](/wiki/Pericardium \"Pericardium\") to fully separate each atrium. The synthetic material [Dacron](/wiki/Dacron \"Dacron\") may also be used to create a repair patch.[\\[9\\]](#cite_note-9)\n\nInserting a catheter has proven to be a safe and successful method for closing the foramen secundum in children.[\\[10\\]](#cite_note-10) This method avoids the symptoms that accompany most ostium secundum atrial septal defects. The catheter is inserted into the [femoral vein](/wiki/Femoral_vein \"Femoral vein\") in the leg and moved into place in the atrial septum. Transesophageal echocardiography is accepted as the method to monitor this procedure which, when performed correctly, has shorter recovery times than surgical intervention.[\\[11\\]](#cite_note-11) Complications of catheter insertion often include nausea and vomiting, blood vessel obstruction, pain, and hemorrhage. The most common problem with this preventive measure is the incomplete closing of the foramen secundum.[\\[12\\]](#cite_note-12)\n\nThere is at present no drug therapy for foramen secundum atrial septal defects, although [infective endocarditis](/wiki/Infective_endocarditis \"Infective endocarditis\") is a postoperative concern. To prevent this condition, a [prophylactic](/wiki/Prophylactic \"Prophylactic\") is used for six months after the operation.[\\[13\\]](#cite_note-13)\n\n### Prognosis\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=6 \"Edit section: Prognosis\")\\]\n\nMany patients with a foramen secundum that persists into adulthood will remain asymptomatic throughout their lives. A mortality rate of less than one tenth of one percent is expected if the operation is performed correctly. Some argue that if the operation is performed before eight years of age, few cardiac abnormalities such as [cardiac dysrhythmia](/wiki/Cardiac_dysrhythmia \"Cardiac dysrhythmia\") are expected later in life.[\\[14\\]](#cite_note-14) Others argue that the operation can take place as late as age 24, to limit cardiac complications in middle age or later. Some sources have argued that [mitral regurgitation](/wiki/Mitral_regurgitation \"Mitral regurgitation\") and [mitral valve prolapse](/wiki/Mitral_valve_prolapse \"Mitral valve prolapse\") are common after age 40, if the ostium secundum is not repaired by age 24.[\\[15\\]](#cite_note-15) Operative closure of atrial septal defects after age 40, and the ability to diminish symptoms at all remains controversial. Some data does suggest that even after that age, symptoms can be alleviated via surgical intervention, including prevention of [Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia](/wiki/Arrhythmogenic_right_ventricular_dysplasia \"Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia\") and other associated cardiac abnormalities.[\\[16\\]](#cite_note-16)\n\n## History\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=7 \"Edit section: History\")\\]\n\nThe discovery of the formation of the foramen secundum and septum secundum was published by P. N. B. Odgers at the [University of Oxford](/wiki/University_of_Oxford \"University of Oxford\") in the [Journal of Anatomy](/wiki/Journal_of_Anatomy \"Journal of Anatomy\") in 1935.[\\[17\\]](#cite_note-17)\n\n## References\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Foramen_secundum&action=edit&section=8 \"Edit section: References\")\\]\n\n1.  ^ [***a***](#cite_ref-gary_1-0) [***b***](#cite_ref-gary_1-1) [***c***](#cite_ref-gary_1-2) Schoenwolf, Gary C., and William J. Larsen. Larsen's Human Embryology. 4th ed. Philadelphia: Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier, 2009. 363. Print.\n2.  **[^](#cite_ref-2)** *Understanding Patent Foramen Ovale*. St, Jude Medical, n.d. Web. 27 November 2012.\n3.  **[^](#cite_ref-3)** *[ped/1686](http://www.emedicine.com/ped/topic1686.htm#)* at [eMedicine](/wiki/EMedicine \"EMedicine\")\n4.  **[^](#cite_ref-4)** Rigatelli, Gianluca (September 2014). [\"Should we consider patent foramen ovale and secundum atrial septal defect as different steps of a single anatomo-clinical continuum?\"](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4178506). *Journal of Geriatric Cardiology*. **11** (3): 177–179\\. [doi](/wiki/Doi_\\(identifier\\) \"Doi (identifier)\"):[10.11909/j.issn.1671-5411.2014.03.004](https://doi.org/10.11909%2Fj.issn.1671-5411.2014.03.004) (inactive 12 July 2025). [ISSN](/wiki/ISSN_\\(identifier\\) \"ISSN (identifier)\") [1671-5411](https://search.worldcat.org/issn/1671-5411). [PMC](/wiki/PMC_\\(identifier\\) \"PMC (identifier)\") [4178506](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4178506). [PMID](/wiki/PMID_\\(identifier\\) \"PMID (identifier)\") [25278963](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25278963).`{{[cite journal](/wiki/Template:Cite_journal \"Template:Cite journal\")}}`: CS1 maint: DOI inactive as of July 2025 ([link](/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_DOI_inactive_as_of_July_2025 \"Category:CS1 maint: DOI inactive as of July 2025\"))\n5.  **[^](#cite_ref-5)** Hanslik A, Pospisil U, Salzer-Muhar U, Greber-Platzer S, Male C. *Predictors of spontaneous closure of isolated secu